  "description": "Cohesion is the linguistic connectedness between sentences — the specific devices that link one sentence to the next so the reader can follow the thread. It is distinguished from coherence, which is the overall logical unity of a text. Cohesion is local; coherence is global.\nM.A.K. Halliday and Ruqaiya Hasan identified five cohesive devices in Cohesion in English (1976):\nReference — pronouns and demonstratives that point back to previously mentioned items. \u0026ldquo;The report was published. It showed\u0026hellip;\u0026rdquo; Substitution — replacing a word or phrase with a substitute. \u0026ldquo;I\u0026rsquo;ll have a coffee. Make that two.\u0026rdquo; Ellipsis — omitting words that the reader can infer. \u0026ldquo;She wrote the first draft. He [wrote] the second.\u0026rdquo; Conjunction — transitional words and phrases that signal the logical relationship between sentences. \u0026ldquo;However,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;therefore,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;in contrast,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;for example.\u0026rdquo; Lexical cohesion — repeating key terms or using synonyms and related words to maintain the topic thread. A paragraph about \u0026ldquo;audience\u0026rdquo; that switches to \u0026ldquo;readers,\u0026rdquo; then \u0026ldquo;users,\u0026rdquo; then \u0026ldquo;the people you\u0026rsquo;re writing for\u0026rdquo; maintains cohesion through lexical variation. Joseph Williams added a structural principle: the \u0026ldquo;old-before-new\u0026rdquo; contract. Each sentence should begin with information the reader already knows (from the previous sentence or from context) and end with new information. This creates a chain where the end of one sentence sets up the beginning of the next [@williams2006].\n",
